      "content": "To optimize your function and reduce runtime complexity for large inputs, consider using a more efficient algorithm for finding prime factors. One common approach is to check for factors only up to the square root of `n`. Here's an optimized version of your function:\n\n```python\ndef find_prime_factors(n):\n    factors = []\n    d = 2\n    while d * d <= n:\n        while (n % d) == 0:\n            factors.append(d)\n            n //= d\n        d += 1\n    if n > 1:\n        factors.append(n)\n    return factors\n```\n\nThis version only checks for factors up to the square root of `n`, significantly reducing the number of iterations and improving the runtime for large inputs.",
