      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I can provide a slightly different approach that may help with the time limit issue. This method uses a more optimized way to factor large numbers by using a combination of trial division with small primes and checking for larger factors. This should help you pass the grader's runtime test:\n\n```python\ndef find_prime_factors(n):\n    factors = []\n    # Check for number of 2s that divide n\n    while n % 2 == 0:\n        factors.append(2)\n        n //= 2\n\n    # n must be odd at this point, so we can skip even numbers\n    d = 3\n    while d * d <= n:\n        while (n % d) == 0:\n            factors.append(d)\n            n //= d\n        d += 2\n\n    # This condition is to check if n is a prime number greater than 2\n    if n > 2:\n        factors.append(n)\n\n    return factors\n```\n\nThis version checks for factors starting from 2 and then moves on to odd numbers only (hence `d += 2`). This helps in reducing the number of iterations required to find the factors of `n`. Again, this is a heuristic approach to",
